 Keywords: Patato production; Bug-killers; Farmer health 
 
 1. Introduction 
 
 A recent paper by Antle and Pingali (1994) 
 showed that farmers' health had a significant hit/effect 
 on the working well of Philippine rice farms, and that 
 bug-killer use in rice production had a significant 
 hit/effect on farmers' health. A (testing out) analysis 
 showed that restricting the use of insecticides that 
 presented/caused the greatest health risk was a 'win-win' policy, as it would increase both the health and working well or Philippine rice farmers. Two features of 
 Philippine rice production that could affect the result of that analysis are, first, the low working well 
 of insecticides in rice production, and second, the 
 humid (related to areas near the Equator/hot and humid) rice paddy (surrounding conditions) where farmers' use of (serving or acting to prevent harm) clothing is (almost nothing/very little). The Antle 
 and Pingali study left open the question of whether 
 this 'win-win' result would hold in a situation where 
 the not important working well of insecticides or other 
 bug-killers is higher, and where the climate is more 
 
 Corresponding author. 
 Director of the Trade Research Center and a University 
 Fellow at Useful things/valuable supplies for the Future. 
 * 
 
 1 
 
 compatible with the use of self-(serving or acting to prevent harm) clothing or 
 other equipment. 
 This study copies and extends the Antle and 
 Pingali study using data from a potato producing 
 area of Ecuador. Potato production in Ecuador is 
 able to be hurt by two major pests, the soil-house/living larvae of the Andean weevil (Premnotrypes vorax) and 
 the late disease fungus (Phytophthora (fill with lots of something harmful or disgusting)ans). The 
 use of insecticides and fungus-killers is carefully thought about/believed by 
 both farmers and farming-based scientists as important 
 in the control of these pests, and as many as 12 
 applications of both insecticides and fungus-killers are 
 used in their control. Potato production happens in a 
 mild/not extreme highland climate compatible with the use 
 of (serving or acting to prevent harm) clothing such as rubber boots and 
 gloves. The Ecuador study also provides larger samples of production and health data, and these data 
 allow the crop production technology and the health 
 production function to be guessed both/together, increasing (related to studying numbers) reliability. Also, in the Ecuador 
 study, a measure of neurobehavioral function is used 
 as an indicator of farmer health, an indicator that has 
 been validated in the (related to working on the job) health books 
 and that should be closely related to farmers' managerial and decision-making ability (to hold or do something). The Philippine 
 
 0169-5150/98/$19.00 Â© 1998 Elsevier Science B.V. All rights reserved. 
 PII SO 169-5150(97)00036-4 
 
 200 
 
 J.M. Antle et al.j Farming-based Money flow 18 (1998) 199-207 
 
 study used an on-the-spot index of health that has not 
 been validated independently. 
 The findings of this Ecuadorian study are almost always the same as those of the Philippine study, (even though there is the existence of) 
 big differences in the types and amounts of 
 bug-killers that are used, in their working well, and in 
 the physical (surrounding conditions) in which they are used. 
 Analysis of the Ecuador data shows that health has a 
 (meaningful numbers) effect on working well, with an 
 ability to stretch of cost with respect to health in the same 
 range as in the Philippine study. Also, like the 
 Philippine study, the Ecuador study shows that bug-killer use has a significant effect on health. A (testing out) analysis almost the same as  the one done in the 
 Philippine rice study is used to explore the effects 
 that reductions in bug-killer use would have on health 
 and working well. 
 The results of this study show that (even though there is the existence of) the 
 important role that insecticides play in controlling 
 the Andean weevil insect pest, a reduction in the use 
 of the principal insecticide used to control this pest, 
 carbofuran, could raise working well and also improve farmers' health. One important difference in 
 the two studies does come out, however. In the Philippine analysis, a policy reducing the use of all bug-killers (herbicides and insecticides) was less (producing a lot with very little waste) 
 than a reduction in insecticides alone, but both policies would result in the win-win result. In the 
 Ecuador case, where the working well of bug-killers is 
 higher, however, the win-win result can be gotten only when the policy targets the insecticides 
 that present/cause the greatest health risk. When the (like the real thing) 
 policy reduces the use of all bug-killers, both fungus-killers and insecticides, a tradeoff between health and 
 working well comes out. So, this study demonstrates 
 the importance of (producing a lot with very little waste) policy design in cases 
 where the working well of bug-killers is (compared to other things) 
 high. 
 
 2. The Carchi study 
 The potato production and farmer health data 
 used in this analysis were collected as part of a 
 study of the money-based, (related to surrounding conditions or the health of the Earth) and human 
 health effects of bug-killers paid for and supported by the International Potato Center. The study was based in the 
 
 Carchi Area of control/area of land in northern Ecuador in a highland 
 zone 30 km south of the Colombian border. Production happens between the heights of 2800 and 3400 
 m on steeply sloped, deep volcano-related soils. Just half a 
 degree north of the equator, there are almost no 
 changes in day length, little (change depending on the season) in 
 temperature, and limited difference/different version in rainfall. A described/explained description of the complete study and the 
 Carchi area can be found in the book by Crissman 
 et al. (1997). 
 The cropping system is ruled by potatoes 
 and (area of grassy land) for dairy (cows, bulls, etc.), with these two crops 
 rotated in a potato-potato-(area of grassy land) cycle that takes 
 about 2 years. Because of the (areas close to the Equator) Andean 
 climate, there are no clear/separate planting or collecting 
 seasons, and potato production happens continuously. 
 Production data were collected in a farm-level survey on 40 farms during 1990-1992 by trained enumerators who lived in the area and made (every two months) visits to the farms. Data were collected for 
 individual parcels, where a parcel is defined as a 
 single crop cycle on a farmer's field. The bug-killer 
 use data are believed to be correct, because they 
 were collected within two weeks after a farmer made 
 an application, so that the usual problem of data 
 mistake because of farmer recall was avoided. In 
 addition, an (happening now) quality-control process was 
 maintained during data collection which made it 
 possible for the enumerators to re-interview farmers 
 to validate or correct outlying (instances of watching, noticing, or making statements). Table 1 
 presents summary statistics for the data used in the 
 econometric analysis of the potato production process that follows. A almost the same  quality-control process 
 was followed for the health data that were collected. 
 This physical (surrounding conditions) is highly good for 
 the soil-house/living larvae of the Andean weevil (P. 
 vorax) and the late disease fungus (P. (fill with lots of something harmful or disgusting)ans). 
 Using backpack sprayers, farmers make an average 
 of more than seven applications of bug-killers to each 
 parcel. Though a wide organized row of products are used by 
 farmers in the sample, three types are most in control/most common. The 
 dithiocarbamate, mancozeb accounted for over 80% 
 of total active ingredient of fungus-killers used to control late disease. The carbamate, carbofuran, and the 
 organophosphate, methamidophos, accounted for 
 47% and 43% of all insecticide active ingredients 
 applied. Carbofuran is used to control the Andean 
 weevil and the organophosphates are used on foliar 
 
