 Antle et al. (1994). 
 
 insect pests. Most farmers manage a few fields, so 
 that potato production and bug-killer use are continuous throughout the year. An important result 
 of continuous production is a year-round potential 
 for (related to working on the job) and (unplanned/minor event) exposure to bug-killers. Bug-killers are not used in the (area of grassy land) cycle and 
 are almost never used in other crops that may be included 
 in the rotation, such as (peas, beans, lentils, etc.). So, a farmer's 
 exposure to bug-killers comes almost completely from 
 potato production. The insecticides used are nerve poisons-they kill the pest by interfering with the 
 functioning of the nervous system. Bug-killers are 
 applied using a backpack sprayer and, in that process, the applicator's clothes often become wet with 
 spray mix. As a result, the major exposure route 
 for the applicator is skin-related, especially through his 
 hands and back. Applicators appear to be aware of at 
 least some of the risks connected with bug-killer use, 
 yet they do not use (serving or acting to prevent harm) clothing that effectively prevent exposure, nor do they show other 
 exposure-avoiding behavior. So, the use of (serving or acting to prevent harm) clothing in this mild/not extreme (surrounding conditions) is almost the same 
 to the (event(s) or object(s) that prove something) from the Philippines study. 
 
 201 
 
 To examine the health hits/effects of bug-killer use, 
 the health research team managed and did/done a survey of the 
 farm population (n = 174) and an age- and education-matched referent group (n = 72) not exposed to 
 bug-killers. All people (who were part of a study, etc.) answered questions on 
 bug-killer use and medical problems, received a medical examination by a field doctor, completed a 
 series of tests of nervous system function and went through blood tests. These tests were oriented towards 
 those effects most likely to be connected with the 
 insecticide and fungus-killer exposures that the farming-based team had written down and that farm members 
 reported over periods of days to years. Crissman et 
 al. (1994) and Cole et al. (1998a) report in other places 
 on the complex exposure pattern and the higher rates 
 of skin problems (skin swelling), reduced vibration feeling/excited feeling, lower cholinesterase levels and generally 
 poorer neurobehavioral test results among the farm 
 population compared to the referent group. 
 Early/incomplete analyses showed that the neurobehavioral tests (showed/shown or proved) the most consistent relationship with recent use of bug-killers within the farm 
 population. Neurobehavioral tests were chosen because psychiatric books pointed to/showed problems among 
 those with long-lasting exposure to organophosphate 
 compounds (Gerchon and Shaw, 1961), disease-related work has written about central nervous system 
 effects of sudden poisoning episodes (Rosenstock et 
 al., 1991) and tests of neurobehavioral function are sensitive measures of such problems in 
 non-medical (groups of people/animals/things) (Anger et al., 1983). We 
 said more about the Neurobehavioral Core Test Battery 
 that was tested cross-culturally and recommended 
 by the World Health Organization (Cassito et al., 
 1990). Individual tests were grouped into functional 
 sub-scales by a neuropsychologist. Many tests 
 was used to test a set of neurobehavioral skills 
 that include attention, visual and (related to space or existing in space) abilities, 
 visual and sound-related reaction times, and motor and 
 psychomotor skills. The test results were (done or made to look the same way every time) so that neurobehavioral status is positively related to the test score. 
 This neurobehavioral measure of bug-killer hits/effects represents a big improvement as compared to the health disabilities index used by 
 Antle and Pingali. The health weakness index is an 
 on-the-spot measure of a few factors guessed to be 
 affected by bug-killer exposure, whereas the neurobe- 
 
 202 
 
 J.M. Antle et al. /Agricultural Money flow 18 (1998) 199-207 
 
 behavioral index used here is taken from a standard&#126;zed t&#126;st which measures only the part of the organIsm directly affected by the nerve poisons. Also, 
 the sample size used in this study is nearly four 
 times the size of the Philippine study. This direct 
 measure eliminates most of the doubt of measuring health effects not starting from bug-killer 
 use. 
 Because of skewed distributions in test scores, we 
 restricted the referent population by age (16-65 inc_1usive) and education ( &amp;gt; 3 years) and developed 
 hnear moving backward (statement about the future) equations based on age 
 and education. These restrictions removed about 20% 
 of people/of the group (see Cole et al. (1997b) for details). 
 A (done or made to look the same way every time) score was then calculated for each 
 test for each farm member who met the age and 
 education restrictions by subtracting the people (who were part of a study, etc.)' 
 (described the future) value for the test from the measured value 
 and dividing the difference by the standard error of 
 t&#126;e estimate came/coming from the referent group regresSIOn. The scores were then averaged across tests in 
 the subscale to get a sub-scale (done or made to look the same way every time) score 
 for each function. Finally, the math mean of the 
 sub-scale (done or made to look the same way every time) scores gave/given an overall 
 neurobehavioral score for modelling purposes. 
 The neurobehavioral scores for the farm population were much lower than those of the referent non-farming population even taking account of 
 differences in age, education and verbal intelligence 
 level. The mean (done or made to look the same way every time) score was almost one 
 standard moving away less than the population not directly exposed to bug-killers and (in a big way) lower 
 than that now (capable of being seen and known) in other working (groups of people/animals/things) exposed to poisonous substances in other places 
 in the world. The mean minimums for the different 
 functions were over three standard mistakes lower 
 pointing to/showing big, medically important shortages i&#126; 
 the basic thinking-related tasks. Such levels of bad behaviors 
 :vould relate with (large/relatively large) (problems, delays, etc.) carrymg out the daily tasks of running a household and 
 making clear decisions in farm management and 
 would be just like the levels found in the 
 neuro-in a thinking-related way weakened on disability (moneys paid regularly after retirement) in 
 countries such as Canada and the United States. The 
 quality of home and working life and the working well of these farm members would this way be expected to 
 be (in a big way) reduced. 
 
 3. Joint guess of the cost function and the 
 health production function 
 Following the logic of the Antle and Pingali 
 model, we suggest/say  a cost function to represent the 
 production process. This cost function is received/made from 
 from a household production model in which farmers' effective management and field labor is a function of their health. From a standard cost-minimization problem, we get the per-hectare changeable cost 
 function C(y, w, z, h), where y is crop yield, w is a 
 vector of factor prices, z represents fixed factors 
 (size of the farmer's field in the model presented 
 here), and his a measure ofthe farmer's health. This 
 cost function shows the usual curviness properties 
 with respect to y and w, and is decreasing in z and 
 h. 
 
 Following Antle and Capalbo (1994), health is 
 assumed to be a function h(e(x, b), c), where e(x, 
 b) is exposure to bug-killers, x, b is a measure of 
 avoiding behavior by the farmer (such as use of 
 (serving or acting to prevent harm) equipment and safe handling practices), 
 and c is a vector of personal (features/ qualities/ traits). There is 
 little difference/different version in avoiding behavior among farmers in 
 the study presented here, so we simplify the presentation to a health production function h( x, c), 
 where h is assumed increasing and curved in x. 
 We use the log-linear guess to the cost 
 function, 
 
