 ventional (detailed description of exactly what is required) of the cost function is used 
 with health left out/kept out from the cost function, a tax on 
 carbofuran or a tax on all bug-killers increases the 
 average changeable cost of production, as money-based 
 explanation (describes the future). Second, when health is included in 
 the cost function, a tax charged and collected on carbofuran alone 
 results in a negative relationship between the tax 
 rate and average cost. This result happens because the 
 positive effect of a higher bug-killer price is more 
 than offset by the cost-reducing effect of improved 
 health. This result is just like the Antle and Pingali 
 finding that a bug-killer tax targeted at insecticides in 
 rice production would increase working well. However, when a tax on all bug-killers is used, a positive 
 relationship comes out because the effect of the tax on 
 cost now goes beyond the effect of health in the cost 
 function. 
 The clear policy hint/result/effect of these findings is 
 that reducing carbofuran use is a win-win suggestion/possible plan: farmers would be both healthier and more 
 productive if carbofuran use were reduced, because 
 the working well gains from improved health outweigh the negative working well effects of reduced 
 bug-killer use. However, a policy to reduce all bug-killer use would be less (producing a lot with very little waste) and would result in a 
 tradeoff between health and working well. 
 In ending/deciding, we note that a bug-killer tax is used 
 in the tests to illustrate the effects of changing 
 bug-killer use. Taxes are representative (reward or reason for doing something)-type 
 policies. Also, available to policy makers are a few 
 types of legal/law-based and other policies. For example, 
 in the United States, high-risk bug-killers can only be 
 applied by trained bug-killer applicators. Many countries also restrict the availability of certain (related to surrounding conditions or the health of the Earth) damaging or dangerous bug-killers, or include rules (related to/looking at/thinking about) on-farm use of risky 
 bug-killers on the product label. There are also important technology and education policy options, including (combined different things together so they worked as one unit) pest management, the development of 
 late-disease resistant varieties, and programs to (help increase/show in a good way) the safe use of bug-killers and the use of 
 (serving or acting to prevent harm) clothing. These policies could improve 
 working well and the health of the farm population 
 without (impressive/forcing (on people)/causing an inconvenient situation) the working well losses that could 
 be connected with reduced bug-killer use. 
 Trade and related exchange rate policies also 
 could affects bug-killer use, 
 (related to surrounding conditions or the health of the Earth) quality, working well and health (Antle 
 
 et al., 1996). Ecuador's exchange rate policies have 
 effectively paid for the importation of bug-killers 
 such as carbofuran by about 30% (Lee and Espinosa, 
 1998). Because this policy change would be equal to a uniform tax on all types of bug-killers, the 
 analysis presented here hints that the elimination 
 of this helping payment would reduce all types of bug-killers 
 and improve health, but could negatively/badly affect working well. 
 
 Responses 
